      "name": "The Remote Work Productivity Paradox",
      "published": "2025-05-20T14:30:00Z",
      "mediaType": "text/markdown",
      "content": "# The Remote Work Productivity Paradox\n\nFive years into the remote work revolution, we're seeing some unexpected trends. While many companies report higher productivity metrics, employee burnout rates have also increased significantly.\n\n## The Numbers Don't Lie\n\nRecent studies show:\n- 73% increase in reported productivity\n- 45% increase in reported burnout\n- 60% of workers putting in longer hours than pre-2020\n\n## What's Really Happening?\n\nThe lines between work and life have blurred beyond recognition. We're more productive in terms of output, but at what cost?\n\n### The Always-On Culture\n\nWithout physical boundaries, many remote workers find themselves checking emails at 10 PM or joining calls during what used to be family time.\n\n### Solutions That Actually Work\n\n1. **Strict Digital Boundaries** - Set specific hours for work communication\n2. **Dedicated Workspace** - Even if it's just a corner of your bedroom\n3. **Regular Check-ins** - Not just about work, but about well-being\n\nHow do you maintain work-life balance while working remotely?",
