      "name": "Web Accessibility in 2025: Progress and Persistent Gaps",
      "published": "2025-05-15T16:45:00Z", 
      "mediaType": "text/markdown",
      "content": "# Web Accessibility in 2025: Progress and Persistent Gaps\n\nThe web accessibility landscape has seen significant improvements over the past few years, but we still have a long way to go. Let's examine where we are and what still needs work.\n\n## The Good News\n\n- Major frameworks now include accessibility features by default\n- Browser support for ARIA has improved dramatically\n- More companies are hiring dedicated accessibility experts\n- Legal compliance has driven widespread adoption of basic standards\n\n## The Persistent Challenges\n\n### Beyond Compliance\n\nMost organizations focus on meeting WCAG AA requirements, but true accessibility goes beyond checkbox compliance. It's about creating genuinely usable experiences for everyone.\n\n### The AI Double-Edged Sword\n\nAI tools can help generate alt text and improve navigation, but they can also create new barriers when not implemented thoughtfully.\n\n## What Developers Can Do Today\n\n1. **Test with actual assistive technologies** - Not just automated tools\n2. **Include users with disabilities in your design process** - From day one, not as an afterthought\n3. **Consider cognitive accessibility** - Not just screen readers\n4. **Make accessibility part of your definition of done** - Not a separate phase\n\n## Resources\n\n- [WebAIM's accessibility evaluation tools](https://webaim.org/)\n- [ARIA Authoring Practices Guide](https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/)\n- [Inclusive Design Principles](https://inclusivedesignprinciples.org/)\n\nAccessibility isn't just the right thing to do - it makes our products better for everyone. What accessibility challenges are you facing in your projects?",
