      "id": "https://sarahstech.blog/posts/open-source-sustainability",
      "name": "The Open Source Sustainability Crisis", 
      "published": "2025-05-10T11:20:00Z",
      "mediaType": "text/markdown",
      "content": "# The Open Source Sustainability Crisis\n\nOpen source software powers the modern internet, but the maintainers behind these critical projects are burning out at an alarming rate. It's time we had an honest conversation about sustainability.\n\n## The Scale of the Problem\n\nConsider that:\n- 96% of applications contain open source components\n- Many critical libraries are maintained by a single person\n- Most maintainers receive no compensation for their work\n- Corporate users rarely contribute back to projects they depend on\n\n## Real Stories from the Trenches\n\nI've spoken with dozens of open source maintainers over the past year. The stories are remarkably consistent:\n\n*\"I spend 20+ hours a week on this project that millions of people use, and I can't even afford to work on it full-time.\"*\n\n*\"The constant pressure to fix bugs and add features, combined with entitled users demanding instant responses, has made this a source of stress rather than joy.\"*\n\n## Sustainable Solutions\n\n### For Companies\n- **Pay for what you use** - If your business depends on open source, budget for it\n- **Contribute more than code** - Documentation, testing, and community management matter too\n- **Sponsor maintainers** - GitHub Sponsors and similar platforms make this easy\n\n### For Individual Developers\n- **Be respectful in issue reports** - Maintainers are humans, not customer service bots\n- **Contribute what you can** - Even small PRs help\n- **Consider maintenance burden** - Before requesting features, think about ongoing complexity\n\n### For Maintainers\n- **Set boundaries** - You don't owe anyone your nights and weekends\n- **Ask for help** - Both technical and financial\n- **It's okay to say no** - To features, to users, to unreasonable demands\n\n## Moving Forward\n\nThe open source ecosystem won't survive on good will alone. We need systemic changes in how we value and support the infrastructure that powers our digital world.\n\nWhat's your experience with open source sustainability? Are you a maintainer struggling with these issues, or a user looking to give back?",
